# Remove commas from 'Price' and 'Vol.' columns
# Remove '%' sign from 'Change %' column
# Remove specific characters from the column names
# Remove "K" in from the volume column. Convert this to float.
bitcoin_data = bitcoin_data.replace({',': ''}, regex=True)
bitcoin_data['Change %'] = bitcoin_data['Change %'].str.rstrip('%').astype(float) / 100
bitcoin_data = bitcoin_data.rename(columns={'Vol.': 'Volume', 'Change %': 'Change'})
bitcoin_data['Volume'] = bitcoin_data['Volume'].replace({'K': ''}, regex=True)
bitcoin_data['Volume'] = bitcoin_data['Volume'].str.replace('K', '0').str.replace('M', '0000').str.replace('B', '0000000').str.replace('.', '').astype(float) * 10 # Assuming 'Vol.' is in thousands

from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose
# Perform seasonal decomposition on the monthly data
decomposition = seasonal_decompose(bitcoin_data['Price'], model='additive', period=30)

# Convert decomposition components to pandas Series for plotting
observed = pd.Series(decomposition.observed, index=bitcoin_data.index)
seasonal = pd.Series(decomposition.seasonal, index=bitcoin_data.index)
trend = pd.Series(decomposition.trend, index=bitcoin_data.index)
resid = pd.Series(decomposition.resid, index=bitcoin_data.index)

# Detect anomalies in the residual component
threshold = 2.5 * resid.std()
anomalies = resid[abs(resid) > threshold]

# Plot the original data with anomalies
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
plt.plot(bitcoin_data.index, bitcoin_data['Price'], label='Prices', color='blue') # Access the 'close' column
plt.plot(trend, label='Trend (12-Month SMA)', color='green')
plt.scatter(anomalies.index, bitcoin_data.loc[anomalies.index, 'Price'], color='red', label='Anomalies') # Use .loc to access values based on index
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Prices')
plt.title('Anomaly Detection on Prices')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# Perform seasonal decomposition on the monthly data
decomposition = seasonal_decompose(bitcoin_data['Price'], model='additive', period=12)

# Convert decomposition components to pandas Series for plotting
observed = pd.Series(decomposition.observed, index=bitcoin_data.index)
seasonal = pd.Series(decomposition.seasonal, index=bitcoin_data.index)
trend = pd.Series(decomposition.trend, index=bitcoin_data.index)
resid = pd.Series(decomposition.resid, index=bitcoin_data.index)

# Detect anomalies in the residual component
threshold = 2.5 * resid.std()
anomalies = resid[abs(resid) > threshold]

# Plot the decomposition components with anomalies
fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3, ax4) = plt.subplots(4, 1, figsize=(14, 12), sharex=True)

observed.plot(ax=ax1, legend=False)
ax1.set_ylabel('Observed', fontsize=12)
ax1.set_title('Seasonal Decomposition of Standardized Closed Prices', fontsize=16)
ax1.grid(True)

seasonal.plot(ax=ax2, legend=False)
ax2.set_ylabel('Seasonal', fontsize=12)
ax2.grid(True)

trend.plot(ax=ax3, legend=False)
ax3.set_ylabel('Trend', fontsize=12)
ax3.grid(True)

resid.plot(ax=ax4, legend=False)
ax4.set_ylabel('Residual', fontsize=12)
ax4.grid(True)
# Add anomalies to the residual plot
ax4.scatter(anomalies.index, anomalies, color='red', label='Anomalies')
ax4.legend()

plt.xlabel("Date", fontsize=12)
plt.tight_layout()

import statsmodels.api as sm

# Assuming monthly_data is your DataFrame with Date as index and Price as a column
# Replace monthly_data with your actual DataFrame

# Perform seasonal decomposition
decomposition = sm.tsa.seasonal_decompose(monthly_data['Price'], model='additive', period=7)  # Assuming monthly seasonality

# Plotting the components
fig, axes = plt.subplots(4, 1, figsize=(10, 10))
monthly_data['Price'].plot(title='Original', ax=axes[0])
decomposition.trend.plot(title='Trend', ax=axes[1])

monthly_data2 = monthly_data.copy()
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming monthly_data2 is already defined and available

# Split the dataset into training and testing sets
training_data = monthly_data2[monthly_data2.index < pd.to_datetime('2023-05-01')]
print("Training data shape:", training_data.shape)

testing_data = monthly_data2[monthly_data2.index >= pd.to_datetime('2023-05-01')]
print("Testing data shape:", testing_data.shape)

# Separate target variable (Price) for ARIMA model
y_train = training_data['Price']
y_test = testing_data['Price']

# Fit ARIMA model with parameters (4,1,2)
arima_order = (1, 1, 2)
arima_model = ARIMA(y_train, order=arima_order)
arima_fitted = arima_model.fit()

# Make predictions on the training data
train_predictions = arima_fitted.predict(start=0, end=len(y_train)-1, typ='levels')

# Make predictions on the testing data
test_start = len(y_train)
test_end = test_start + len(y_test) - 1
test_predictions = arima_fitted.predict(start=test_start, end=test_end, typ='levels')

# Calculate evaluation metrics for training data
train_mse = mean_squared_error(y_train, train_predictions)
train_rmse = np.sqrt(train_mse)
train_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_train - train_predictions) / y_train)) * 100

# Calculate evaluation metrics for testing data
test_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, test_predictions)
test_rmse = np.sqrt(test_mse)
test_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_test - test_predictions) / y_test)) * 100

# MASE calculation
# Calculate in-sample one-step naive forecast error
naive_forecast_train = training_data['Price'].shift(1)
naive_forecast_error_train = np.abs(training_data['Price'][1:] - naive_forecast_train[1:])
naive_mae_train = np.mean(naive_forecast_error_train)

# Calculate MASE for training data
train_mase = mean_absolute_error(y_train, train_predictions) / naive_mae_train

# Calculate in-sample one-step naive forecast error for testing data
naive_forecast_test = testing_data['Price'].shift(1)
naive_forecast_error_test = np.abs(testing_data['Price'][1:] - naive_forecast_test[1:])
naive_mae_test = np.mean(naive_forecast_error_test)

# Calculate MASE for testing data
test_mase = mean_absolute_error(y_test, test_predictions) / naive_mae_train

print("Evaluation Metrics for Training Data:")
print(f"**Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):** {train_rmse}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE):** {train_mape}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE):** {train_mase}")

print("\nEvaluation Metrics for Testing Data:")
print(f"**Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):** {test_rmse}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE):** {test_mape}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE):** {test_mase}")

# Extend the date index for forecast
forecast_dates = pd.date_range(start=testing_data.index[-1], periods=12, freq='M')[1:]

# Make predictions for the forecast period
forecast_start = test_end + 1
forecast_end = forecast_start + len(forecast_dates) - 1
forecast_predictions = arima_fitted.predict(start=forecast_start, end=forecast_end, typ='levels')

# Plot actual vs predicted prices including forecast
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))

# Plot the original prices

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming monthly_data2 is already defined and available

# Split the dataset into training and testing sets
training_data = monthly_data2[monthly_data2.index < pd.to_datetime('2023-05-01')]
print("Training data shape:", training_data.shape)

testing_data = monthly_data2[monthly_data2.index >= pd.to_datetime('2023-05-01')]
print("Testing data shape:", testing_data.shape)

# Separate target variable (Price) for ARIMA model
y_train = training_data['Price']
y_test = testing_data['Price']

# Fit ARIMA model with parameters (4,1,2)
arima_order = (4, 1, 2)
arima_model = ARIMA(y_train, order=arima_order)
arima_fitted = arima_model.fit()

# Make predictions on the training data
train_predictions = arima_fitted.predict(start=0, end=len(y_train)-1, typ='levels')

# Make predictions on the testing data
test_start = len(y_train)
test_end = test_start + len(y_test) - 1
test_predictions = arima_fitted.predict(start=test_start, end=test_end, typ='levels')

# Calculate evaluation metrics for training data
train_mse = mean_squared_error(y_train, train_predictions)
train_rmse = np.sqrt(train_mse)
train_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_train - train_predictions) / y_train)) * 100

# Calculate evaluation metrics for testing data
test_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, test_predictions)
test_rmse = np.sqrt(test_mse)
test_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_test - test_predictions) / y_test)) * 100

# MASE calculation
# Calculate in-sample one-step naive forecast error
naive_forecast_train = training_data['Price'].shift(1)
naive_forecast_error_train = np.abs(training_data['Price'][1:] - naive_forecast_train[1:])
naive_mae_train = np.mean(naive_forecast_error_train)

# Calculate MASE for training data
train_mase = mean_absolute_error(y_train, train_predictions) / naive_mae_train

# Calculate in-sample one-step naive forecast error for testing data
naive_forecast_test = testing_data['Price'].shift(1)
naive_forecast_error_test = np.abs(testing_data['Price'][1:] - naive_forecast_test[1:])
naive_mae_test = np.mean(naive_forecast_error_test)

# Calculate MASE for testing data
test_mase = mean_absolute_error(y_test, test_predictions) / naive_mae_train

print("Evaluation Metrics for Training Data:")
print(f"**Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):** {train_rmse}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE):** {train_mape}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE):** {train_mase}")

print("\nEvaluation Metrics for Testing Data:")
print(f"**Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):** {test_rmse}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE):** {test_mape}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE):** {test_mase}")

forecast_start = test_end + 1

Diagnostic Checking¶

After estimating the model, the goodness of fit of the model and some assumptions should be checked.

The following assumptions should be satisfied

  • Errors must be Normal distribution with 0 mean.
  • Errors must be independent from each other (i.e WN).
  • Error variance must be constant (Homoscedastic)

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming monthly_data2 is already defined and available

# Split the dataset into training and testing sets
training_data = monthly_data2[monthly_data2.index < pd.to_datetime('2023-05-01')]
print("Training data shape:", training_data.shape)

testing_data = monthly_data2[monthly_data2.index >= pd.to_datetime('2023-05-01')]
print("Testing data shape:", testing_data.shape)

# Separate features and target variable
X_train = training_data[['Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Volume', 'Change']]
y_train = training_data['Price']

X_test = testing_data[['Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Volume', 'Change']]
y_test = testing_data['Price']

# Hyperparameter tuning using GridSearchCV
param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 0.2],
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 7],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4],
    'subsample': [0.8, 1.0]
}

gbr = GradientBoostingRegressor(random_state=42)
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=gbr, param_grid=param_grid, cv=3, n_jobs=-1, verbose=2, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Best parameters from GridSearchCV
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
print(f"Best parameters found: {best_params}")

# Create and train the Gradient Boosting model with the best parameters
gbr_model = GradientBoostingRegressor(**best_params, random_state=42)
gbr_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the training and testing data
train_predictions = gbr_model.predict(X_train)
test_predictions = gbr_model.predict(X_test)

# Calculate evaluation metrics for training data
train_mse = mean_squared_error(y_train, train_predictions)
train_rmse = np.sqrt(train_mse)
train_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_train - train_predictions) / y_train)) * 100

# Calculate evaluation metrics for testing data
test_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, test_predictions)
test_rmse = np.sqrt(test_mse)
test_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_test - test_predictions) / y_test)) * 100

# MASE calculation
# Calculate in-sample one-step naive forecast error
naive_forecast_train = training_data['Price'].shift(1)
naive_forecast_error_train = np.abs(training_data['Price'][1:] - naive_forecast_train[1:])
naive_mae_train = np.mean(naive_forecast_error_train)

# Calculate MASE for training data
train_mase = mean_absolute_error(y_train, train_predictions) / naive_mae_train

# Calculate in-sample one-step naive forecast error for testing data
naive_forecast_test = testing_data['Price'].shift(1)
naive_forecast_error_test = np.abs(testing_data['Price'][1:] - naive_forecast_test[1:])
naive_mae_test = np.mean(naive_forecast_error_test)

# Calculate MASE for testing data
test_mase = mean_absolute_error(y_test, test_predictions) / naive_mae_train

print("Evaluation Metrics for Training Data:")
print(f"**Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):** {train_rmse}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE):** {train_mape}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE):** {train_mase}")

print("\nEvaluation Metrics for Testing Data:")
print(f"**Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):** {test_rmse}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE):** {test_mape}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE):** {test_mase}")

# Extend the date index for forecast
forecast_dates = pd.date_range(start=testing_data.index[-1], periods=12, freq='M')[1:]

# Extend the features for forecast (you need to adjust this based on your specific forecasting method)
# For simplicity, we'll use the last available data point as a proxy for forecasting future values
last_available_data = testing_data.iloc[-1][['Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Volume', 'Change']].values
extended_features = np.tile(last_available_data, (len(forecast_dates), 1))

# Make predictions for the forecast period
forecast_predictions = gbr_model.predict(extended_features)

# Plot actual vs predicted prices including forecast
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))

# Plot the original prices
plt.plot(monthly_data2.index, monthly_data2['Price'], label='Original', color='blue')

# Plot the training predictions
plt.plot(training_data.index, train_predictions, label='Training Predictions', color='orange')

# Plot the testing predictions
plt.plot(testing_data.index, test_predictions, label='Testing Predictions', color='red')

# Add a vertical line to separate training and testing data
plt.axvline(x=pd.to_datetime('2023-05-01'), color='gray', linestyle='--')

# Plot the forecast

plt.xlabel('Date')

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from catboost import CatBoostRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming monthly_data2 is already defined and available

# Split the dataset into training and testing sets
training_data = monthly_data2[monthly_data2.index < pd.to_datetime('2023-05-01')]
print("Training data shape:", training_data.shape)

testing_data = monthly_data2[monthly_data2.index >= pd.to_datetime('2023-05-01')]
print("Testing data shape:", testing_data.shape)

# Separate features and target variable
X_train = training_data[['Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Volume', 'Change']]
y_train = training_data['Price']

X_test = testing_data[['Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Volume', 'Change']]
y_test = testing_data['Price']

# Hyperparameter tuning using GridSearchCV
param_grid = {
    'iterations': [100, 200, 300],
    'depth': [4, 6, 8, 10],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 0.2],
    'l2_leaf_reg': [1, 3, 5, 7, 9],
    'border_count': [32, 64, 128]
}

catboost = CatBoostRegressor(random_seed=42, silent=True)
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=catboost, param_grid=param_grid, cv=3, n_jobs=-1, verbose=2, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Best parameters from GridSearchCV
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
print(f"Best parameters found: {best_params}")

# Create and train the CatBoost model with the best parameters
catboost_model = CatBoostRegressor(**best_params, random_seed=42, silent=True)
catboost_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the training and testing data
train_predictions = catboost_model.predict(X_train)
test_predictions = catboost_model.predict(X_test)

# Calculate evaluation metrics for training data
train_mse = mean_squared_error(y_train, train_predictions)
train_rmse = np.sqrt(train_mse)
train_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_train - train_predictions) / y_train)) * 100

# Calculate evaluation metrics for testing data
test_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, test_predictions)
test_rmse = np.sqrt(test_mse)
test_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_test - test_predictions) / y_test)) * 100

# MASE calculation
# Calculate in-sample one-step naive forecast error
naive_forecast_train = training_data['Price'].shift(1)
naive_forecast_error_train = np.abs(training_data['Price'][1:] - naive_forecast_train[1:])
naive_mae_train = np.mean(naive_forecast_error_train)

# Calculate MASE for training data
train_mase = mean_absolute_error(y_train, train_predictions) / naive_mae_train

# Calculate in-sample one-step naive forecast error for testing data
naive_forecast_test = testing_data['Price'].shift(1)
naive_forecast_error_test = np.abs(testing_data['Price'][1:] - naive_forecast_test[1:])
naive_mae_test = np.mean(naive_forecast_error_test)

# Calculate MASE for testing data
test_mase = mean_absolute_error(y_test, test_predictions) / naive_mae_train

print("Evaluation Metrics for Training Data:")
print(f"**Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):** {train_rmse}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE):** {train_mape}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE):** {train_mase}")

print("\nEvaluation Metrics for Testing Data:")
print(f"**Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):** {test_rmse}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE):** {test_mape}")
print(f"**Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE):** {test_mase}")

# Extend the date index for forecast
forecast_dates = pd.date_range(start=testing_data.index[-1], periods=12, freq='M')[1:]

# Extend the features for forecast (you need to adjust this based on your specific forecasting method)
# For simplicity, we'll use the last available data point as a proxy for forecasting future values
last_available_data = testing_data.iloc[-1][['Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Volume', 'Change']].values
extended_features = np.tile(last_available_data, (len(forecast_dates), 1))


# Create lagged features for forecasting
def create_lagged_features(data, lags=12):
    df = data.copy()
    for lag in range(1, lags + 1):
        df[f'lag_{lag}'] = df['Price'].shift(lag)
    df.dropna(inplace=True)
    return df

# Extend the dataset with lagged features

X_train = training_data[['Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Volume', 'Change']]
y_train = training_data['Price']

X_test = testing_data[['Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Volume', 'Change']]
y_test = testing_data['Price']

# Function to perform grid search and return the best model
def perform_grid_search(model, param_grid, X_train, y_train):
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid=param_grid, cv=3, n_jobs=-1, verbose=2, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
    grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
    return grid_search.best_estimator_

# Hyperparameter tuning for Random Forest
rf_param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'max_features': ['auto', 'sqrt', 'log2'],
    'max_depth': [10, 20, None],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4],
    'bootstrap': [True, False]
}

# Hyperparameter tuning for Gradient Boosting

    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 0.3],
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 7],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4]
}

gb_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

rf_train_predictions = rf_model.predict(X_train)
rf_test_predictions = rf_model.predict(X_test)

gb_train_predictions = gb_model.predict(X_train)
gb_test_predictions = gb_model.predict(X_test)

# Combine the predictions for the hybrid model
train_predictions = (rf_train_predictions + gb_train_predictions) / 2
test_predictions = (rf_test_predictions + gb_test_predictions) / 2

# Calculate evaluation metrics for training data
train_mse = mean_squared_error(y_train, train_predictions)

# Calculate evaluation metrics for testing data
test_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, test_predictions)
test_rmse = np.sqrt(test_mse)
test_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_test - test_predictions) / y_test)) * 100

naive_forecast_train = training_data['Price'].shift(1)
naive_forecast_error_train = np.abs(training_data['Price'][1:] - naive_forecast_train[1:])
naive_mae_train = np.mean(naive_forecast_error_train)

import pandas as pd

from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingRegressor

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

    'max_depth': [3, 5, 7, 10, None],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4]
}

dt = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=42)
grid_search_dt = GridSearchCV(estimator=dt, param_grid=param_grid_dt, cv=3, n_jobs=-1, verbose=2, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
grid_search_dt.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Best parameters from GridSearchCV for Decision Tree
best_params_dt = grid_search_dt.best_params_
print(f"Best parameters for Decision Tree found: {best_params_dt}")

# Create and train the Decision Tree model with the best parameters
dt_model = DecisionTreeRegressor(**best_params_dt, random_state=42)
dt_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

param_grid_gb = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'max_depth': [3, 4, 5],

}

    'max_features': ['auto', 'sqrt', 'log2'],
    'max_depth': [10, 20, None],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4],
    'bootstrap': [True, False]
}
rf_model = perform_grid_search(RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42), rf_param_grid, X_train, y_train)

# Hyperparameter tuning for CatBoost
cb_param_grid = {
    'iterations': [100, 200, 300],
    'depth': [4, 6, 10],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 0.3],
    'l2_leaf_reg': [1, 3, 5, 7, 9]
}
cb_model = perform_grid_search(CatBoostRegressor(random_state=42, verbose=0), cb_param_grid, X_train, y_train)

# Hyperparameter tuning for Gradient Boosting
gb_param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 0.3],
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 7],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4]
}
gb_model = perform_grid_search(GradientBoostingRegressor(random_state=42), gb_param_grid, X_train, y_train)

# Fit the models
rf_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
cb_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
gb_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the training and testing data
rf_train_predictions = rf_model.predict(X_train)
rf_test_predictions = rf_model.predict(X_test)

cb_train_predictions = cb_model.predict(X_train)
cb_test_predictions = cb_model.predict(X_test)

gb_train_predictions = gb_model.predict(X_train)
gb_test_predictions = gb_model.predict(X_test)

# Combine the predictions for the hybrid model
train_predictions = (rf_train_predictions + cb_train_predictions + gb_train_predictions) / 3
test_predictions = (rf_test_predictions + cb_test_predictions + gb_test_predictions) / 3

# Calculate evaluation metrics for training data
train_mse = mean_squared_error(y_train, train_predictions)
train_rmse = np.sqrt(train_mse)
train_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_train - train_predictions) / y_train)) * 100

# Calculate evaluation metrics for testing data
test_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, test_predictions)
test_rmse = np.sqrt(test_mse)
test_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_test - test_predictions) / y_test)) * 100

# MASE calculation
# Calculate in-sample one-step naive forecast error
naive_forecast_train = training_data['Price'].shift(1)

naive_mae_train = np.mean(naive_forecast_error_train)

# Calculate in-sample one-step naive forecast error for testing data
naive_forecast_test = testing_data['Price'].shift(1)
naive_forecast_error_test = np.abs(testing_data['Price'][1:] - naive_forecast_test[1:])
naive_mae_test = np.mean(naive_forecast_error_test)

# Calculate MASE for testing data
test_mase = mean_absolute_error(y_test, test_predictions) / naive_mae_train
